    babyData.put(1, [
      "<h2><strong><em>Maternity Application (Baby First Week)</em></strong></h2> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <p><strong>Your Baby at Week 1&nbsp;</strong></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>In week 1 of pregnancy, there is no baby size! You may ask, 'How/why? Well, that is because your body is preparing to deliver a mature egg from one of your ovaries!&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>If the sperm and egg meet at the right time, you will find out you are pregnant in a few weeks.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your baby's gender is determined the moment sperm and egg combine! Your baby's sex has already been decided, even though you won't be able to see it.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>The sperm cell determines whether you will have a boy or girl, although the egg cell carries an X chromosome by default. When the winning sperm contains an X chromosome, an XX zygote or girl will be born. You will have a boy or an XY zygote if there is a Y chromosome.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>In addition to gender, your baby's physical features, including eye color, hair color, and skin color, are also determined at the moment of conception.</span></p>"
    ]);
    babyData.put(2, [
      "<h2><strong><em>Maternity Application (Baby 2nd Week)</em></strong></h2> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Ovulation&nbsp;</strong></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Ovulation occurs on day 14, at the end of this week. At this point, the ovary releases the egg into the fallopian tube, where it gets ready for fertilization by your partner's sperm.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>You only need one sperm to reach the egg and penetrate it. Once this happens, the egg quickly undergoes changes that stop additional sperm from fertilizing it.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>The newly fertilized egg starts to divide into cells quickly within 24 hours. It will continue to divide for around three weeks as it slowly enters the fallopian tube towards the uterus. It takes around three days for it to go to the uterus, where it transforms from a single, solid ball into a ball of cells filled with fluid, called a blastocyst.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>At this point, your growing baby is simply a little ball of cells, yet it will grow amazingly quickly. It has three cell masses: an exterior one that will become the placenta, an inner one that will become the embryo, and a fluid-filled cavity that will become the amniotic sac.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>It's amazing to know that your baby's genetic makeup, including gender, is complete when your egg is fertilized.&nbsp; </span></p>"
    ]);
    babyData.put(3, [
      "<h2><strong><em>Maternity Application (Baby 3rd Week)</em></strong></h2> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Implantation</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>During the third week of pregnancy, after ovulation, you make amazing progress toward becoming a mother.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>At week 3 of pregnancy, your growing blastocyst has travelled down your fallopian tube to your uterus. It may implant itself in the lush uterine lining by the end of this week or the start of the next (A process known as 'hatching' occurs when the blastocyst sheds its transparent outer shell before implanting.) Some women experience little implantation bleeding or discomfort.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>By the end of this week, the blastocyst will be attached to the endometrium (uterine lining). The implantation in the uterus creates a connection. The developing embryo (baby-to-be) receives oxygen and nutrients from the endometrium. Over time, the implantation site will grow into the placenta.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>This week, your baby is just a tiny ball with 100 cells, known as an embryo. Your baby's genetic features, including gender, will be created from conception. Every day, your little miracle makes amazing progress as it prepares for the incredible adventure of growth and development.</span></p>"
    ]);
    babyData.put(4, [
      "<h2><strong><em>Maternity Application (Baby 4th Week)</em></strong></h2> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Your Growing Baby in Week 4</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>In week 4, your embryo is just a tiny ball of cells. Now, your baby is just the size of a poppy seed!</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>The newly formed embryo has three layers that will eventually become your baby: the middle layer (mesoderm) forms the skeleton, muscles, kidney, blood vessels, and heart; the outer layer (ectoderm) forms the nervous system, teeth, and skin; and the inner layer, endoderm, form the lungs, liver, digestive system, and pancreas.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>The heart and nerve system of your baby-to-be are already developing. Blood is beginning to circulate and create blood vessels. The umbilical cord connects you and your child and will form from some of these blood vessels.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Detecting your baby's heartbeat or seeing it on an ultrasound may be too early, but hold on to hope! Every day brings a new milestone and progress toward a fully formed human being!</span></p>"
    ]);
    babyData.put(5, [
      "<h2><strong><em>Maternity Application (Baby 5th Week)</em></strong></h2> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Your Baby at Week 5</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>During this week, your baby is around the size of a sesame seed and looks more like a tadpole than a human. Your unborn child's heart is already beating and pumping blood, even though you may not yet look pregnant. As the heart gets divided into chambers, it'll find a regular beat.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Along with additional essential organs, your baby's kidneys, liver, intestines, and pancreas begin to grow. Your baby's arms and legs will eventually grow from developing the upper and lower limb buds.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>As we move up, the retina's initial form develops. The nose becomes defined, and the adorable features of the face also develop.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>It's amazing how many body organs start developing, even if your baby is still pretty small.&nbsp;</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Baby's Growing Appearance</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>However, your baby's appearance is mostly determined by its genetic makeup. Your baby's features are programmed, much like a blueprint, and this programming begins the moment sperm and egg connect (the earliest stage of conception)&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>During the first month of pregnancy, your baby's hair color, eye shape, height, and body structure, among many other characteristics, are already defined. But you won't be able to fully see them until after you give birth, or even later as your child becomes a toddler. </span></p>"
    ]);
    babyData.put(6, [
      "<h2><strong><em>Maternity Application (Baby 6th Week)</em></strong></h2> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Your Baby Development at Week 6</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>The embryo grows week by week at a staggering pace. Your baby is around the size of a pomegranate seed at week six.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>What's going on inside your pregnant belly at week 6? There's so much going on at week six! Your baby's features are also beginning to develop. Your baby's eyes will be the dark stains, its nose will be the openings, and its ears will be the pits.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>While the fingers are forming now, the hands and feet resemble paddles. The heart is already beating twice as quickly as yours&mdash;roughly 150 beats per minute&mdash;though it's hard to believe.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>It's too early to feel your baby's initial movements now. You will get a hang of your baby's aerobics-like movements in the second and third trimesters!</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>The average embryo is about 0.5 cm this week and will double in size again next week. Amazing!</span></p>"
    ]);
    babyData.put(7, [
      "<h2><strong><em>Maternity Application (Baby 7th Week)</em></strong></h2> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Your Little One at Week 7</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>It's an incredible accomplishment for both you and your baby to reach week seven!</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>What a wonderful thing this is: Around 100 new brain cells are being created by your 7-<h2><strong><em>Maternity Application (Baby 7th Week)</em></strong></h2> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Your Little One at Week 7</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>It's an incredible accomplishment for both you and your baby to reach week seven!</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>What a wonderful thing this is: Around 100 new brain cells are being created by your 7-week embryo every minute! Your baby's heart and brain are growing.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>During this week, all of the essential organs began to form. The intestines, brain, heart, and circulatory system continue growing and becoming more complex every day.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Baby is developing recognizable facial features such as ears, nostrils, a mouth, and a tongue. While they can't see yet, its tiny retinas are beginning to form and prepare for a lifetime of seeing the world.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Importantly, the baby's arm and leg joints are growing, and a permanent set of kidneys is emerging.&nbsp;</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Your Baby Size</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your baby's size is like a blueberry. Your embryo measures between 1.2 cm (crown to rump) and has doubled in size since last week.&nbsp;</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Umbilical Cord at Week 7</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your baby starts forming the characteristic C shape this week, which persists even after delivery.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>With the head pointing toward the abdomen and the knees tucked toward the chest, your baby will tuck into what is called the fetal position. This form helps the umbilical cord stay in place as it emerges from your baby's tummy.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>A crucial part of the early pregnancy anatomy is the umbilical cord. Consider it your baby's lifeline, a means of communication with you. You can feed your baby by giving them air and nutrients through the umbilical cord. In week seven, the cord starts to take shape.</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>The width and length of the cord increase as your pregnancy goes on and your baby develops.</span></p> week embryo every minute! Your baby's heart and brain are growing.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>During this week, all of the essential organs began to form. The intestines, brain, heart, and circulatory system continue growing and becoming more complex every day.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Baby is developing recognizable facial features such as ears, nostrils, a mouth, and a tongue. While they can't see yet, its tiny retinas are beginning to form and prepare for a lifetime of seeing the world.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Importantly, the baby's arm and leg joints are growing, and a permanent set of kidneys is emerging.&nbsp;</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Your Baby Size</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your baby's size is like a blueberry. Your embryo measures between 1.2 cm (crown to rump) and has doubled in size since last week. </span></p>"
    ]);
    babyData.put(8, [
      "<h2><strong><em>Maternity Application (Baby 8th Week)</em></strong></h2> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Your Growing Baby is Now a Fetus</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>When your baby reaches week eight, you can celebrate because your baby is now a fetus instead of an embryo&mdash;the embryonic tail has finally vanished!</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your baby's organs are developing during this crucial time, even if it is extremely early on. The baby's muscles and nerves start to work at this early stage. Although the baby isn't moving much right now, it constantly shifts and moves.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>They even begin getting some eye color, which may surprise you. Fun fact: babies' taste buds rapidly develop as they prepare for their first foods.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your cutie is as big as a raspberry and measures about 1.6 cm (crown to rump). It grows about a millimeter each day.</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Know More About Your Baby?&nbsp;</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your baby is having a great time during week eight! Your baby is now practicing moving inside your womb, even though it is still too small to feel anything. Your baby's limbs constantly grow, so it occasionally stretches its arms, hands, legs, and feet.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>It's comforting to know that your baby is becoming more active even though you won't feel any movement until at least week 18. This is especially true if you observe it during an ultrasound scan!</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your baby's heart is also developing incredibly in the interim. As of this week, it has already split into the right and left chambers. The little one's heartbeat is now up to 150 beats per minute, roughly twice as quickly as your own! </span></p>"
    ]);
    babyData.put(9, [
      "<h2><strong><em>Maternity Application (Baby 9th Week)</em></strong></h2> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Baby Growth at Week 9</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>The baby is growing more distinct facial features and honing that charm inside your week nine pregnant belly. In the meantime, the division of your baby's heart into four chambers has just finished. The formation of the valve has begun.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your baby's body is still developing and beginning to look more like a human every week.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Although the eyes are fully developed, the eyelids won't open until week 27. Though they won't be able to tell you whether they are male or female for a few more weeks, your child's outward sex organs are present.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Now, your baby is the size of a cherry. Your 9-week fetus measures 2.3 cm (crown to rump).</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Insights into Your Baby's Formation</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Baby now has ear lobes, fingers and toes, and a little nose. The baby's embryo status is reaching its final week, so the head is getting rounded and straightened. Their knee, elbow, shoulder, ankle, wrist, and ankle joints are all working, and their arms are now bent at the elbow, which is ideal for working out those muscles!&nbsp;</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Know About Baby Breathes Inside</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Babies do not breathe when they are still in the womb. Although they do perform breathing-like movements&ndash;your baby receives oxygen from you when you breathe through the umbilical cord.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Just keep in mind that your baby's lungs still develop during pregnancy, so they require oxygen.</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>At nine weeks, babies begin to practice breathing-like movements, which can be observed on a normal ultrasound at week 10. This exciting developmental stage gets the lungs ready for the baby's first breath after birth!</span></p>"
    ]);
    babyData.put(10, [
      "<h2><strong><em>Maternity Application (Baby 10th Week)</em></strong></h2> <h2><strong>Baby at Week 10</strong></h2> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Week 10 is a pivotal time in your pregnancy, filled with rapid developments for both you and your growing baby.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>The baby is now a fetus, not an embryo! These two terms just define different phases of growth. Major organs, such as the brain, heart, and lungs, along with the arms and legs, are formed during the embryonic phase. These organs and parts are developed once you have a fetus and are currently growing and developing.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>At this point, the baby's head is around half the length of its body and has rounded out. Their forehead has a little protrusion to allow their brain to grow.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your tiny wriggler grows so fast day by day! With functional arm joints, they can flex their elbows for the first time, and bones and cartilage are growing. These bones will get stronger and visible on a standard ultrasound!</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Hair and fingernails are beginning to show, too! And within your ten-week pregnant belly, your baby is busy practicing swallowing and kicking. Can you believe that?&nbsp;</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>First Teeth in the Womb</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>It's true&mdash;babies start growing teeth long before birth, despite popular belief that they begin at six months. Although they haven't shown up yet, the first teeth have already begun to form.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>You might be surprised by the news that your baby is already developing its first set of teeth, just behind the gums, as early as week 10 of pregnancy. These are undoubtedly tiny.</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>This is the perfect time for your baby's first set of teeth to erupt because the bones are also growing fast at this time. Those gorgeous whites will have to wait until their moment shines through! </span></p>"
    ]);
    babyData.put(11, [
      "<h2><strong><em>Maternity Application (Baby 11th Week)</em></strong></h2> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Your Growing Baby at Week 11</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>The baby is moving smoothly and elegantly inside your 11-week pregnant belly. The skin of your 11-week-old fetus is transparent now, but it will soon become more opaque. The baby's fingers and toes are no longer webbed at 11 weeks. Tooth buds, hair follicles, and nail beds are all developing on the baby's face. Baby can also open and shut its mouth. Pretty cool, hmm?&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Equally amazing? The baby's left and right hemispheres of the brain are still developing. While the right side helps the baby process language, the left half controls logic.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>The baby's gender may not be revealed to you for weeks. However, the baby's outside sexual organs are beginning to develop into either male (a penis) or female (a labia majora and clitoris) parts. The most exciting part is that your doctor will probably be able to hear your heartbeat when they use a Doppler stethoscope.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Baby is now as big as a Fig! Your 11-week fetus is 4.1 cm (crown to rump).&nbsp;</span></p> <h2><br /><br /></h2> <h2><strong>Baby First hiccups</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>At week 11, your baby looks more like a tadpole, but don't underestimate your little one! You might not feel your baby's hiccups yet, as he or she may already be learning.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Why does your baby hiccup so early? As the diaphragm develops, your baby is now swallowing amniotic fluid, which causes hiccups. It's perfectly normal. Imagine your baby practicing all these life skills.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your baby may not give you hiccups until you are 27 weeks pregnant. Your baby is still too little for you to feel any movement at this time.</span></p>"
    ]);
    babyData.put(12, [
      "<h2><strong><em>Maternity Application (Baby 12th Week)</em></strong></h2> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Your baby update from week 12</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your little one is growing fast during this week!</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your 12-week-old fetus is almost done growing all of the essential organs and systems in your baby's body. Your baby has fully functional digestive, urinary, and circulatory systems and all its bones, muscles, limbs, and organs. This suggests that it is already consuming liquor and urinating (don't worry, this is only amniotic fluid!).&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Yes, the baby is going to enter the period of growth and maturation, during which time its tissues and organs will expand and grow quickly.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>A baby at 12 weeks opens and closes its fingers and curls its toes! Your baby's appearance has now become more recognized as human, with a defined nose and chin</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>At 12 weeks pregnant, the baby is as big as a lime. The average 12-week fetus is about 5.4 cm (crown to rump). Go, baby, go!</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Baby's Fingernails</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Around week 11, your baby's fingernails grow early, beginning with the nail beds. Nails begin growing from these beds at week 12. Mom-to-be, just imagine you'll be trimming them soon!</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>The development from the nail bed gets bigger every week once the nails start to show. Your baby's nails develop quickly, but don't worry&mdash;they won't start scratching yet.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your baby's fingers and toenails will be long enough to reach the fingertips by week 34. Long nails are not a problem during pregnancy because your baby is covered in lubricating amniotic fluid and protective substances.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>They are now entering a rapid growth and refinement phase as they prepare for the journey towards birth.</span></p>"
    ]);
    babyData.put(13, [
      "<h2><strong><em>Maternity Application (Baby 13th Week)</em></strong></h2> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Your baby update from week 13</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your little love has grown to be the size of a peach as you celebrate the end of the first trimester. It's still very small, but it's in progress to grow! Additionally, around week 13, your baby is starting to grow fingerprints, a distinctive feature of humans!&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>The baby's skin is still relatively transparent at this stage, but lanugo, a fine, silky hair, begins to cover it.&nbsp;</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <p><strong>Vocal Cords Formation</strong></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>During your 13th week of pregnancy, your fetus has vocal cords, teeth, and fingerprints (wow!)</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your baby is working hard at week 13 on developing the speech patterns necessary for saying his/her first words. The development of vocal cords marks the beginning of the promise of laughter, cries, and the first words.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Of course, you can't hear anything from your baby now because sound cannot travel through the uterus. When your baby learns to cry and speak, these vocal cords will develop more, so don't panic if they aren't used for months.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>The mouth is growing more and more developed as you wonder how these voice cords evolve (many thanks to your baby's developing neural and skeletal systems, too). At a normal ultrasound scan, you might even notice your baby sucking its thumb!</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <p><strong>What more is happening inside that?</strong></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your baby is not only busy developing its vocal cords but also its intestines, which are growing rapidly! Little bones start growing in his arms and legs at 13 weeks pregnant.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>This week, the intestines are still developing inside the umbilical cord cavity, but they will shortly move permanently to your baby's abdominal cavity, where they will continue to develop.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>The placenta is also expanding and securely attached to the umbilical cord not far along your baby's abdomen. The placenta and the umbilical cord are your baby's lifelines for nutrition, even if the digestive system won't be able to process food just yet. </span></p>"
    ]);
    babyData.put(14, [
      "<h2><strong><em>Maternity Application (Baby 14th Week)</em></strong></h2> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Your Little One at Week 14</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Wow! You've entered the second trimester officially!</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>A 14-week-old baby is wiggling its toes, putting its adorable little fingers to its adorable little mouth (maybe even sucking its thumb! ), and swaying its head around. This is possibly the most exciting milestone! Your baby's brain is still developing, which enables the facial muscles to squint, frown, and grimace. Consider them warm-up exercises that your baby will use when it grows into childhood!</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>The digestive system is also actively developing. Red blood cell production is starting in the spleen, and bile production is starting in the liver.</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Early lanugo and hair</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>When it comes to the physical features of your baby's development in your womb, week 14 is an amazing milestone! Your little wriggler may be starting to grow hair this week.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Even though you have to wait until the end of the third trimester to expect a head full of hair, it's still an amazing development to see a little hair growing on your baby's body. Some hair may be present on the head and brows, but it is still light or thin.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Also, very fine, small hairs sprout from the thin skin on your baby's body. Known as lanugo, these provide warmth to your baby swimming in amniotic fluid.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>But don't worry; lanugo vanishes right before childbirth. After birth, if you notice them, they disappear quickly. Keep in mind that your baby will gain weight later in the pregnancy, so lanugo will finally have its use.</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Other Development in this Week</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>It may seem incredible, but your baby shifts about every five minutes. You can't feel anything yet, so it could be difficult to accept, especially since this is your first pregnancy. However, when you do, it feels as though you have butterflies in your stomach!&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your baby is now able to move all of its limbs and joints. Movement occurs in the head, arms, hands, legs, feet, and mouth. Watching your baby turn and wriggle during an ultrasound scan is exciting.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>If you aren't feeling anything just yet, don't worry. It doesn't mean that the baby is not in motion. Particularly if the placenta is positioned in front of your uterus, it functions as a cushion. Most pregnant women won't feel the baby's movements for a few more weeks.&nbsp;</span></p>"
    ]);
    babyData.put(15, [
      "<h2><strong><em>Maternity Application (Baby 15th Week)</em></strong></h2> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Your Growing Baby at Week 15</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>At 15 weeks pregnant, the baby is as big as an apple. You'll be shocked to know that your baby can already sense light during this week. For a few more months, the eyes stay closed, but as soon as they open, they will begin to blink!</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Additionally, your baby can now hiccup. The fingernails are now completely developed. The external genitals may become fully developed as your pregnancy progresses.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your baby starts to practice breathing, sucking, and swallowing to teach itself the essential survival abilities needed when they emerge from your cozy womb and settle into your cozy home.&nbsp;</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Baby Bone Development</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>At week 15, how do you believe your baby's bones are developing? Your baby has a lot of getting up to do, as an adult has 206 bones, therefore they are going through an enormous growth spurt!&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Now, your baby's head measures half the length of the body. Its forehead has a visible protrusion as well, allowing space for healthy brain development.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your baby is also participating in daily fitness sessions, kicking, curling toes, and moving its little arms and legs. Because your fetus is only a few ounces in weight, you won't feel these baby&rsquo;s movements happening inside your belly.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>More importantly, calcium is necessary for your baby's bones to grow and develop properly. These develop quite quickly, and once you feel your baby kick, you'll realize how quickly they expand!&nbsp;</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Mouth motions in boys versus girls</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Can you believe that as early as 15 weeks, your baby can open and close their mouth? Have you heard that there are so-called differences in what boys and girls do at this stage?</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>According to scientists, girls move their mouths more than boys do. According to some theories, this is because girls are considered more developmentally advanced than males, although every baby develops differently. </span></p>"
