    babyData.put(16, [
      "<h2><strong><em>Maternity Application (Baby 16th Week)</em></strong></h2> <h2><strong>Your Growing Baby at Week 16</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your baby is now the size of an avocado at 16 weeks! It's the fourth month of your pregnancy, and your baby is growing quickly!</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Inside your womb, your kid kicks, hiccups, and moves. Your little one also plays with the umbilical cord as well! It's okay; your baby can only grab and release it at most.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>By now, your baby's taste buds have developed. An ultrasound scan will clarify that the skeleton is also growing into bones. The circulatory and urinary systems are two of the more sophisticated bodily systems that are now functional.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Baby's facial development is improving, too: eyes and ears are blinking and frowning. Even at week 16, your baby's skin is still extremely thin and nearly transparent. You might literally see the tiny, delicate blood vessels under the skin if you could take a closer look at your child right now.&nbsp;</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>What else is your little one doing at 16 weeks?</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>The second trimester is when babies develop the most, and a 16-week fetus is no different. Now, your baby's important organs are developing.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your baby has more lung tissue forming, its bones are starting to harden, its pancreas and liver are making, and even its toenails are growing. Lungs simply inhale and exhale amniotic fluid, not oxygen, when your baby practices breathing-like moments. Keep in mind that your baby receives nutrition and oxygen from you through the placenta and umbilical cord.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your baby's heart is still quite small, but it beats very well! The little heart in such a tiny person can continuously pump about 25 quarts of blood per day! Put simply, this is a big week for the baby!&nbsp;</span></p> <h2><br /><br /></h2> <h2><strong>Does your baby have taste buds?&nbsp;</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Of course! Your baby's taste buds have developed by 16 weeks, and because the neurons have formed by 8 weeks, your little one is now sensitive to specific flavors.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>It may surprise you to know that the amniotic fluid has a flavor similar to food. Your baby can try many flavors, especially strong ones like curry and garlic. The amniotic fluid's flavor may also be sweet if you consume sugary foods.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>However, research indicates that most babies choose sweet flavors because this helps them grow to love breast milk. After giving birth and seeing your child grow, you could notice that your baby has already begun to show a preference for particular foods.&nbsp;</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>One more interesting fact?</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>By week 16, the ear structures that control hearing are already well-formed, but they will continue to grow over the following few weeks.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>What... What does this mean? This week is the first time your baby will hear your voice! In fact, throughout the next few months, your voice will be the clearest sound your kid can hear. For now, your baby will be able to hear bodily sounds like air entering your lungs and your stomach gurgling.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>This week's most exciting milestone might be your baby's ability to hear and know your voice from birth. So speak to your baby and allow dad to talk to your little one as well! You can also play a song for your baby at this stage, and you'll be shocked to learn that they know it from birth!&nbsp;</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>According to studies, a baby may hold the memory of a lullaby it heard in the womb. So, let's sing your baby a beautiful lullaby! Your newborn will be able to identify a well-known song and voice. </span></p>"
    ]);
    babyData.put(17, [
      "<h2><strong><em>Maternity Application (Baby 17th Week)</em></strong></h2> <h2><strong>Baby is Developing Fast at Week 17</strong></h2> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your little resident is around the size of a pear at 17 weeks and will continue to grow over the next few months.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Now, the baby's soft cartilage is turning into bone. Your baby is gaining weight and developing muscle in those bones, which will help the baby's body perform essential tasks like temperature regulation and metabolism.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>The vernix, a slick, white substance that works as a barrier that protects the skin from amniotic fluid, develops in the baby about this period.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>The baby's ears have nearly reached their final position. Rather than on the sides, the eyes are now positioned forward. The majority of your baby's reactions, including the sucking and swallowing ones that will be useful after delivery, are fully formed by now!&nbsp;</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Baby&rsquo;s Adorable Facial Expressions</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>This week, your baby should start to move their muscles more as the brain is now controlling their heart rate. At this point, your baby can play with their hands and bend and extend their limbs.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Now that the facial muscles are moving, your baby can express a wide range of facial emotions. However, he/she has no control over these expressions yet.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Now, your little one is practicing making facial expressions before birth, just like when a baby is practicing breathing movements before it can actually breathe.</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Early Accumulation of Fat</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Developing body fat in the womb can benefit the developing baby by encouraging healthy brain development and lowering the likelihood of certain illnesses.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>While fat accumulates rapidly during the last trimester, early fat tissues start accumulating around week 17. These will make your little pear appear more like a baby! Early fat deposits help define your baby's fine features this week.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Remember that fats eventually replace lanugo in regulating the body's temperature, so early fat tissues are now beginning to play a crucial role.&nbsp;</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Although the formation of fat may not be happening quickly now, it will happen shortly! </span></p>"
