    babyData.put(18, [
      "<h2><strong><em>Maternity Application (Baby 18th Week)</em></strong></h2> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Baby Growth at Week 18&nbsp;</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>What's your baby doing in your tummy at eighteen weeks pregnant? A lot! Now, your baby is exercising its muscles and learning how to do various actions. Is it really true that the baby is swallowing, sucking, hiccupping, and yawning? They're punching, kicking, twisting, rolling, and they're big enough that you might feel them doing it!&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your baby is growing up so quickly! Your baby weighs roughly the same as a bell pepper right now. Your resident is now able to hear and feel! The movement of the baby's chest also resembles breathing, but the baby is simply consuming amniotic fluid, not air. Until delivery, your sweetie won't truly breathe in oxygen.&nbsp;</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Gender of Your Baby</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>This week, the development of other structures like the genitals, the myelin covering coating around the nerves, and fingerprints continues. This week, if you plan an ultrasound scan, you may be able to find out your baby's gender!&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>If you are having a girl, the vagina, uterus, and fallopian tubes are in place. If you're having a boy, the genitals are distinct and identifiable. We hope your baby doesn't try to hide them when you get an ultrasound!</span></p> <h2><br /><br /></h2> <h2><strong>Week 18th Nervous System</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Even though your baby's nervous system has been growing during the early stages of conception, this week marks a significant developmental milestone for this fascinating bodily system.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>This is due to the beginning of myelin formation surrounding the nerves. This cover is essential for brain communication and shielding your baby's nerves. They also speed up the messages that are transmitted between neurons. Many birth defects may arise in the absence of myelin.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Up until the age of 12 months or so, myelin forms. Remember that the nervous system includes the five senses as well: taste, smell, hearing, touch, and sight. After birth, these senses continue to develop quickly.</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Yawning During this Time</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>What more moves can your tiny athlete perform? Leaps, thumbsucks, head turns, arm flexions, and knee twists. Your baby has picked up a new ability this week: yawning.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Yawning is a common behavior connected to fatigue, sleepiness, and lack of interest, although its exact meaning is unknown. Can your baby truly be bored in the womb? You should be shocked that your child now has this ability despite any doubts.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>If you're lucky, you might capture your baby yawning during your ultrasound scan once more. What a comforting sight that is. Remember to request a picture!</span></p>"
    ]);
    babyData.put(19, [
      "<h2><strong><em>Maternity Application (Baby 19th Week)</em></strong></h2> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>19-week Baby Development</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your baby weighs about as much as a pomegranate at 19 weeks of pregnancy. As expected, lots of changes are taking place now!</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Vernix caseosa, a gooey layer shielding skin from amniotic fluid, has completely covered your baby. If you notice this from birth, don't worry&mdash;it won't last very long.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>This week also marks the beginning of sensory development. The five senses&mdash;taste, smell, sight, hearing, and touch&mdash;are developing in separate brain regions. Neuron development slows down during this time, but connections become deeper.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>The kidneys in your baby still produce urine. The girl or boy you are carrying already has about six million eggs in her ovaries, but this is decreasing. Your baby will have roughly a million eggs when he/she is born.&nbsp;</span></p> <h2><br /><br /></h2> <h2><strong>Vernix Cover Your Baby</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>You've heard a lot about the silly material that covers your child. The kind of plant known as vernix caseosa.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>It is understandable why vernix appears white, feels oily, and seems fairly disagreeable, as it is a combination of dead skin cells, oil from your baby's glands, and the soft, downy hair known as lanugo.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>But it's not as ugly as you would think&mdash;especially when you consider the advantages it offers your child. Vernix is at its thickest during week 19, so you might wish to read up on its significance.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your baby's delicate skin is shielded by the waxy layer, especially if not much fat has yet developed. While the amniotic fluid cushions your baby, the vernix keeps them from appearing overly wrinkly.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>It's common to observe some vernix after giving birth to your child. This lets you see it up close and personal, but don't worry&mdash;it will go soon.&nbsp;</span></p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <h2><strong>Baby Movement at Week 19</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>For any expecting mother, the second trimester&mdash;actually the entire pregnancy&mdash;is a magical period. This week, especially when the movements are obvious, is significant because it's the first time that the thought of having a baby soon starts to kick in.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>You will have begun to feel your baby move at 19 weeks. Most expectant mothers begin to feel movement between weeks 18 and 20. If you've previously been pregnant, you'll experience symptoms sooner rather than later.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Note your initial feelings about your baby and share them with a doctor. This is a crucial part of the prenatal checkup process. You will start to experience more regular movements as your pregnancy goes on! </span></p>"
